    "slug": "signs-of-cyberbullying",
    "title": "Signs Your Child Is Being Cyberbullied - And What to Do About It",
    "date": "April 1, 2026",
    "readTime": 7,
    "category": "Cyberbullying",
    "excerpt": "Most parents do not find out their child is being cyberbullied until it has been going on for weeks. These are the signs to watch for.",
    "metaDescription": "Learn the signs of cyberbullying in children, how to start the conversation, and exactly what to do including how to report it.",
    "content": "<p>Cyberbullying is one of the most common and least visible forms of harm children face today. Unlike playground bullying, it follows children home. Most parents do not find out until it has been happening for weeks or months.</p><h2>What Cyberbullying Actually Looks Like</h2><p>It might look like: being excluded from a group chat, someone sharing a photo without permission, an anonymous account leaving unkind comments, being tagged in something humiliating, or rumours being spread through social media.</p><h2>Warning Signs to Watch For</h2><p><strong>Changes in device behaviour.</strong> A child who was relaxed about their phone suddenly tensing when a notification arrives, turning their screen away, or dramatically reducing use of a device they used to love.</p><p><strong>Emotional changes after going online.</strong> If your child regularly comes away from screen time in a worse mood, that pattern is worth paying attention to.</p><p><strong>Avoiding school or social situations.</strong> Cyberbullying almost always involves people the child knows. If your child is becoming reluctant to attend school, something is usually wrong.</p><p><strong>Disturbed sleep.</strong> Late-night messages, compulsive checking, and anxiety all interfere with sleep.</p><h2>How to Start the Conversation</h2><p>Start by creating the conditions for them to talk. Go for a drive. Have a conversation side by side rather than face to face. Start with something low-stakes. When they do talk: listen more than you speak, do not immediately move to solutions, do not take their devices, and take it seriously however minor it might seem.</p><h2>What to Do Once You Know</h2><p><strong>Document everything</strong> before reporting or deleting. Screenshot every piece of content with dates and usernames. <strong>Report to the school</strong> - schools have a duty to act on cyberbullying involving their pupils. <strong>Report to the platform</strong> - every major platform has reporting mechanisms. <strong>Contact police if necessary</strong> for threats or sustained harassment.</p><div style=\"background:#F0FDF4;border:2px solid #0EA5A0;border-radius:12px;padding:24px 28px;margin:40px 0;\"><h3 style=\"color:#0B1F3A;margin-top:0;\">Shield Protect Your Family With Our Online Safety Courses</h3><p style=\"color:#374151;\">Our <strong>Growing Minds</strong> and <strong>Family Anchor</strong> courses cover cyberbullying in depth.</p><p style=\"color:#374151;margin-bottom:0;\"><a href=\"/courses\" style=\"color:#0EA5A0;font-weight:600;\">Explore Our Courses</a></p></div>"
