    "slug": "screen-time-limits-for-kids",
    "title": "Screen Time Guidelines for Children: What Actually Works by Age",
    "date": "April 1, 2026",
    "readTime": 7,
    "category": "Parent Guidance",
    "excerpt": "Screen time guidelines confuse more parents than they help. Here is a clearer, more practical way to think about it by age and type of use.",
    "metaDescription": "Practical screen time guidelines for children by age. Learn what the research actually says and how to set limits that stick.",
    "content": "<p>Screen time is one of the most debated topics in modern parenting. Official guidelines, conflicting research, and the practical reality of daily family life rarely align. This guide cuts through the noise and gives you a practical, age-by-age framework.</p><h2>What the Research Actually Says</h2><p>What matters is not just how much time children spend on screens, but what they are doing on them. Passive consumption affects children differently from active, creative, or social use. An hour of video chat with grandparents is not the same as an hour of autoplay YouTube. The evidence is clear that excessive, unstructured screen use before bed and on social media is associated with sleep disruption, anxiety, and attention difficulties.</p><h2>Age-by-Age Guidelines</h2><p><strong>Under 18 months:</strong> Avoid screen use other than video calls.</p><p><strong>18 months to 2 years:</strong> If you introduce screens, watch together and keep it brief.</p><p><strong>2-5 years:</strong> No more than one hour per day of high-quality programming. Always watch with your child where possible.</p><p><strong>6-12 years:</strong> Set consistent limits on time and type. One to two hours of recreational screen time per day. No screens during meals, homework, or in bedrooms at night.</p><p><strong>13 and older:</strong> Focus on boundaries around type of use, particularly social media, and times of day. No phones at night, no devices during meals, protected time for homework.</p><h2>The Screen-Free Times That Matter Most</h2><p>Focus on protecting mealtimes, the hour before bed, and the first thirty minutes of the morning. These three windows matter more than counting minutes across the rest of the day.</p><h2>Signs of Too Much Screen Time</h2><p>Watch for: difficulty stopping when asked, irritability after screens are put away, declining interest in offline activities, interference with sleep or schoolwork, and social withdrawal in favour of online-only interaction.</p><div style=\"background:#F0FDF4;border:2px solid #0EA5A0;border-radius:12px;padding:24px 28px;margin:40px 0;\"><h3 style=\"color:#0B1F3A;margin-top:0;\">Shield Protect Your Family With Our Online Safety Courses</h3><p style=\"color:#374151;\">Our <strong>Family Anchor</strong> course covers healthy digital habits in depth including how to set boundaries that work for your family.</p><p style=\"color:#374151;margin-bottom:0;\"><a href=\"/courses\" style=\"color:#0EA5A0;font-weight:600;\">Explore Our Courses</a></p></div>"
