    "slug": "teenager-sexting-risks",
    "title": "Sexting and Teenagers: What Parents Need to Know and What to Say",
    "date": "April 1, 2026",
    "readTime": 8,
    "category": "Teen Safety",
    "excerpt": "Sexting among teenagers is more common than most parents realise. Here is how to talk about it before it becomes a problem.",
    "metaDescription": "Understand the risks of teen sexting, why teenagers do it, the legal implications, and how to have an effective conversation with your child.",
    "content": "<p>Sexting is one of the most uncomfortable conversations parents feel they need to have, and one of the most commonly avoided. But avoidance does not protect teenagers. Understanding does.</p><h2>How Common Is It?</h2><p>Research consistently shows that sexting is far more common among teenagers than most parents realise. Studies suggest that between 15 and 28 percent of teenagers have sent a sexually explicit image, and significantly more have received one.</p><h2>Why Teenagers Do It</h2><p>Teenagers do not sext because they have poor judgement. They do it because they are navigating the same desires for intimacy and connection that every generation has navigated, but with tools that previous generations did not have. Sending an image can feel like intimacy, like proof of trust. Peer pressure plays a significant role.</p><h2>The Real Risks</h2><p><strong>Loss of control.</strong> Once an image is sent, it cannot be unsent. It can be screenshotted, forwarded, or used as coercion.</p><p><strong>Legal risk.</strong> In the UK, creating, sending, or possessing a sexually explicit image of anyone under 18 is a criminal offence regardless of consent.</p><p><strong>Psychological harm.</strong> Having an intimate image shared without consent causes genuine, lasting harm.</p><h2>What to Say Before It Becomes a Problem</h2><p>Keep it practical rather than moral. Once an image is sent, you have no control over where it goes. If anyone asks you for an image, you are allowed to say no. If you have sent something and you are worried, you can tell me and you will not be in trouble.</p><div style=\"background:#F0FDF4;border:2px solid #0EA5A0;border-radius:12px;padding:24px 28px;margin:40px 0;\"><h3 style=\"color:#0B1F3A;margin-top:0;\">Shield Protect Your Family With Our Online Safety Courses</h3><p style=\"color:#374151;\">Our <strong>Nest Breaking</strong> and <strong>Family Anchor</strong> courses cover this topic with practical language for parents and teenagers.</p><p style=\"color:#374151;margin-bottom:0;\"><a href=\"/courses\" style=\"color:#0EA5A0;font-weight:600;\">Explore Our Courses</a></p></div>"
