    "slug": "parental-controls-setup-guide",
    "title": "How to Set Up Parental Controls on iPhone and Android: A Step-by-Step Guide",
    "date": "April 1, 2026",
    "readTime": 9,
    "category": "Practical Guides",
    "excerpt": "Parental controls are not a complete solution, but they are a useful starting point. Here is how to set them up properly.",
    "metaDescription": "Step-by-step guide to setting up parental controls on iPhone, Android, YouTube, and gaming platforms.",
    "content": "<p>Parental controls are not a silver bullet, but as a first line of defence for younger children they are genuinely useful if set up correctly.</p><h2>Apple Screen Time (iPhone and iPad)</h2><p>Go to Settings, then Screen Time, then Turn On Screen Time. If setting it up for a child, select This is my child's device. Key features to configure: Downtime to set hours when the device can only be used for calls and approved apps; App Limits to set daily time limits per category; Communication Limits to control who your child can contact; Content and Privacy Restrictions to prevent explicit content and restrict app installation. Set a Screen Time passcode different from the device passcode to prevent your child from turning settings off.</p><h2>Google Family Link (Android)</h2><p>Download the Family Link app on both your device and your child's. Create a Google account for your child through the setup process. Key features: approve or block app downloads, set daily screen time limits, set a bedtime when the device locks, see your child's location, and view app activity.</p><h2>YouTube and YouTube Kids</h2><p>For children under ten, use YouTube Kids rather than regular YouTube. For older children on regular YouTube, enable Restricted Mode under Settings, then General. For children under 13, enabling SafeSearch on Google and using YouTube Kids is significantly more effective than Restricted Mode alone.</p><h2>Gaming Platforms</h2><p>PlayStation has Family Management through PlayStation Network for spending limits, content ratings, and playtime limits. Xbox has the Microsoft Family Safety app for scheduling and content filters. Nintendo Switch has an excellent parental controls app for time limits and content restrictions.</p><h2>The Honest Limitation</h2><p>All of these controls can be circumvented by a determined teenager with a VPN or a friend's device. They are most effective for younger children and as a support to conversations, not a replacement for them.</p><div style=\"background:#F0FDF4;border:2px solid #0EA5A0;border-radius:12px;padding:24px 28px;margin:40px 0;\"><h3 style=\"color:#0B1F3A;margin-top:0;\">Shield Protect Your Family With Our Online Safety Courses</h3><p style=\"color:#374151;\">Our <strong>Family Anchor</strong> course goes beyond the technical, giving parents the confidence to have the conversations that parental controls alone cannot have for you.</p><p style=\"color:#374151;margin-bottom:0;\"><a href=\"/courses\" style=\"color:#0EA5A0;font-weight:600;\">Explore Our Courses</a></p></div>"
